I think `get_fieldsets` is what you&#39;re looking for

```python
class JournalEntriesAdmin(admin.ModelAdmin):
    list_display = (&#39;EngagementCode&#39;, &#39;EngagementManager&#39;, &#39;EngagementIncharge&#39;)
    list_filter = (&#39;published&#39;, &#39;EngagementCode&#39;)
    search_fields = (&#39;EngagementCode&#39;, &#39;EngagementManager&#39;, &#39;EngagementIncharge&#39;)

    def get_fieldsets(self, request, obj=None):
        if request.user.is_superuser:
            fieldsets = (
                    (None, {  # label 1: None
                        &#39;fields&#39;: ( # dictionary
                            (&#39;EngagementCode&#39;, &#39;EngagementManager&#39;),
                        )
                    }),
                    (&#39;More details&#39;, { # under label 2 : More details
                        &#39;classes&#39;: (&#39;collapse&#39;,),  # css-class : minimized
                        &#39;fields&#39;: (
                            (&#39;published&#39;),
                        )
                    })
                )
        else:
            fieldsets = super().get_fieldsets(request, obj)
        return fieldsets
```

Note you will have to return either fieldsets or an empty tuple for no fieldsets, so you will need to decide what to return if the user is not a superuser. I have just called `super` in the else statement for now.

You can also control what fields appear on a add/change page with `get_fields`.

Also if you wanted to control what actions, filters and columns appear on the list view page depending on the user you can use `get_actions`, `get_list_filter` and `get_list_display` respectively.

